lidar_df =
  lidar |> 
  mutate(id = row_number())

lidar_df |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = range, y = logratio)) +
  geom_point()

Create dataframes

train_df = 
  sample_frac(lidar_df, size = .8) |> 
  arrange(id)

test_df = anti_join(lidar_df, train_df, by = "id")

Look at these

ggplot(train_df, aes(x= range, y = logratio)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_point(data = test_df, color = "red")

Fit a few models to train_df

linear_mod = lm(logratio ~ range, data = train_df)
train_df |> 
  add_predictions(linear_mod) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = range, y = logratio)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red")

mgcv::gam for non-linear models

smooth_mod = mgcv::gam(logratio ~ s(range), data = train_df)
wiggly_mod = mgcv::gam(logratio ~ s(range, k = 30), sp = 10e-6, data = train_df)
train_df |> 
  add_predictions(smooth_mod) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = range, y = logratio)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red")

train_df |> 
  add_predictions(wiggly_mod) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = range, y = logratio)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red")

Try computing our root mean squared errors (RMSEs) for each model.[prediction accuracy] Smaller RMSE = better predictive accuracy.

rmse(linear_mod, test_df)
## [1] 0.1142953
rmse(smooth_mod, test_df)
## [1] 0.06827538
rmse(wiggly_mod, test_df)
## [1] 0.08299499

Iterate!

crossv_mc preforms the training / testing split multiple times, a stores the datasets using list columns

cv_df = 
  crossv_mc(lidar_df, n = 100) |> 
  mutate(
    train = map(train, as_tibble),
    test = map(test, as_tibble)
  )

Or I could make a function

lidar_lm = function(df){
  lm(logratio ~ range, data = df)
}

cv_df = 
  cv_df |> 
  mutate(
    linear_fits = map(train, lidar_lm),
    smooth_fits = map(train, \(df) mgcv::gam(logratio ~ s(range), data = df)),
    wiggly_fits = map(train, \(df) mgcv::gam(logratio ~ s(range, k = 50), sp = 10e-8, data = df))
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    rmse_linear = map2_dbl(linear_fits, test, rmse),
    rmse_smooth = map2_dbl(smooth_fits, test, rmse),
    rmse_wiggly = map2_dbl(wiggly_fits, test, rmse)
  )
cv_df |> 
  select(starts_with("rmse")) |> 
  pivot_longer(
    everything(),
    names_to = "model",
    values_to = "rmse",
    names_prefix = "rmse_"
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x= model, y = rmse)) +
  geom_violin()

Example: Child Growth

growth_df = read_csv("./data/nepalese_children.csv")
## Rows: 2705 Columns: 5
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","

Weight vs arm_c

growth_df |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = weight, y = armc)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

The plots suggests some non-linearity, especially at the low end of the weight distribution

growth_df =
  growth_df |> 
  mutate(
    weight_cp7 = (weight > 7) * (weight - 7)
  )
linear_mod = lm(armc ~ weight, growth_df)
pwl_mod = lm(armc ~ weight + weight_cp7, growth_df)
smooth_mod = mgcv::gam(armc ~ s(weight), data = growth_df)
growth_df |> 
  add_predictions(linear_mod) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = weight, y = armc)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5)+
  geom_line(aes(y= pred), color = "red")

growth_df |> 
  gather_predictions(linear_mod, pwl_mod, smooth_mod) |> 
  mutate(model = fct_inorder(model)) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = weight, y = armc)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red") + 
  facet_grid(~model)

Cross validate!

cv_df =
  crossv_mc(growth_df, 100) |> 
  mutate(
    train = map(train, as_tibble),
    test = map(test, as_tibble))

cv_df = 
  cv_df |> 
  mutate(
    linear_mod = map(train, \(df) lm(armc ~ weight, data = df)),
    pwl_mod = map(train, \(df) lm(armc ~ weight + weight_cp7, data = df)),
    smooth_mod = map(train, \(df) mgcv::gam(armc ~ s(weight), data = df))
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    rmse_linear = map2_dbl(linear_mod, test, rmse),
    rmse_pwl = map2_dbl(pwl_mod, test, rmse),
    rmse_smooth = map2_dbl(smooth_mod, test, rmse),
  )
cv_df |> 
  select(starts_with("rmse")) |> 
  pivot_longer(
    everything(),
    names_to = "model",
    values_to = "rmse",
    names_prefix = "rmse_"
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x= model, y = rmse)) +
  geom_violin()
